KCNA Blasts Japan's Scheme to Scuttle Six-Party Talks 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- A working group meeting for the normalization of the DPRK-Japan relations recently took place in Hanoi under a joint agreement reached at the third session of the fifth round of the six-party talks on February 13. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Many countries hoped measures would be discussed for the normalization of the bilateral relations based on Japan's redemption of its inglorious past and solution of pending issues between the two countries at the meeting. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan, however, insisted on the repatriation of all the abductees it claims still alive, probe into the truth and extradition of criminals, etc. saying that the diplomatic relations can be opened only when the "abduction issue" is settled, to begin with. It even made far-fetched assertions that the issue can not be considered as settled although it was confirmed that some of the victims are no longer alive and all of the abductees should be repatriated to Japan on the premises that all of them are alive. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The working meeting thus failed to reach any agreement due to Japan's wrong act of seriously violating the spirit of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration and that of the February 13 joint document. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This is an inevitable product of the deliberate moves of the present ruling quarters and the right-wing forces of Japan who do not want the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and the normalization of the bilateral relations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Prior to the meeting, Prime Minister Abe blustered that "Japan should approach the meeting, pursuant to the policy which calls on it not to participate in the energy assistance if no progress is made in the settlement of the 'abduction issue.'" Foreign Minister Aso, too, uttered that "Japan cannot provide even a single yen for energy assistance if no progress is made in this respect." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is not hard to guess how the delegation to the meeting had behaved to represent the stand of the authorities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK, therefore, is compelled to clarify its stand as regards the "energy assistance" touted by Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK has never asked Japan for any assistance and it has no idea of getting any help from it, either. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It did not build its economy with others' help in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  It is the DPRK's avowed principled stand to consolidate and develop the independent national economy with its technology and resources. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For Japan to claim that without Japan's energy assistance the DPRK would face great difficulties in its economic development is nothing but a ridiculous calculation of those who know nothing about its economy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The energy assistance to the DPRK was what the six parties including Japan agreed upon at the talks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK does not care about whether Japan gives energy assistance to it or not because it would not affect much the DPRK's economic development. This is its message to the Japanese statesmen. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 But what Japan should do unconditionally is to apologize and compensate for the crimes committed by it against the Korean people in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the recent meeting Japan sidestepped the issue of settling such hideous crimes committed against humankind as forcible drafting and kidnapping of at least 8.4 million Koreans, killing of more than one million of them and recruitment of 200,000 "comfort women" for the imperial Japanese army, even distorting the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang Declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The present Japanese chief executive is a grandson of A class war criminal and the foreign minister is a descendant of the Asos who forcibly took Koreans to coal mines, forcing them to do slave labor. Therefore, they are obliged to more honestly and humbly reflect on the crimes committed by Japan than any others and have the crimes committed by their forefathers settled. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Nevertheless, they instructed their delegates to vociferate at the meeting about the "abduction issue" which had found its settlement thanks to the DPRK's sincere efforts, while turning aside from the issue of redressing Japan's past. How brazen-faced the present Japanese statesmen are. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Explicitly speaking, Japan should settle its past in such a manner as to convince the Korean people by way of compensating for the damage done to them and the crimes perpetrated against them. The hideous crimes committed by Japan against humanity should be settled as a separate issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK strongly demands Japan stop talking about the "abduction issue" but redeem the crimes committed by it in the past which are more horrendous than the issue and sincerely implement the agreement reached at the six-party talks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's failure to do so would only betray its true colors as a mean country behaving quite contrary to the promise and good faith it had said honor before the international community. Then it will stand further ostracized and isolated worldwide.

Japan Urged to Apologize and Compensate for Its Past Crimes  
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- The U.S. Group for the Study of Songun Politics and the U.S. Solidarity Committee for Supporting the Anti-imperialist National Democratic Front and the Struggle of People in south Korea issued a joint statement on Mar. 12 urging Japan to apologize and compensate for the crimes committed by it against the Korean people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Expressing full support to the just actions of the Korean people demanding Japan settle its past crimes, the statement termed Japan's behavior denying its sexual slavery the most impudent action and distortion of the historical facts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The world progressive and revolutionary organizations and figures demand Japan immediately apologize and compensate for its past crimes and abandon its militarist ambition, it stressed.

S. Korean Authorities Urged to Allow Int'l Joint Anti-War Actions 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- The People's Action for Opposing the Troop Dispatch of south Korea reportedly called a press conference in Seoul on Mar. 15 at which it made public a declaration of figures of different circles demanding the south Korean authorities immediately pull back the south Korean troops dispatched overseas and allow a rally and march as part of international joint anti-war actions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Speakers at the press conference accused the "government" of going to dispatch troops overseas, talking about the "state interests," declaring that if this is allowed, this would record the ill-fame of being a criminal state in the history of the Korean nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They termed the action taken by the "government" to disallow the rally and march in Seoul an action to violate even the elementary norm of democracy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A declaration read out at the press conference branded the south Korean "government" again contemplating the dispatch of south Korean troops overseas, talking a lot about the south Korea-U.S. "alliance," as an assistant faithful to the U.S. that has grown corpulent by dint of war and aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The servile attitude of the present "government" towards the barbarous war of the U.S. aimed at aggression and plunder will only justify its logic of world supremacy, the declaration noted, holding that the peaceful rally and march of people for preserving conscience and justice should be allowed under any circumstances.

Establishment of Fair International Order Called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- It would be possible to get rid of old international order characteristic of domination and subjugation and the world order of domination whereby the stronger prey upon the weaker and create a free and peaceful environment only when a new and fair international order is established, says Rodong Sinmun in a signed article Tuesday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Noting that it is an urgent requirement of the times to establish a new and fair international order, the article goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Only when such an international order is established can all arbitrary practices, interference and inequality be eliminated in the international relations, the sovereignty of all countries and nations be respected and defended, the principle of equality and impartiality be strictly observed and interference in the internal affairs of other countries and nations and strong-arm and arbitrary practices be brought to an end. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The present international order is an old and partial one under which the imperialists openly infringe upon the sovereignty of other countries and a jungle law holds sway. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Making no secret of their wild ambition to establish a system of their global domination, the imperialists resort to infringement upon the sovereignty of the countries standing in their way and those situated in major zones rich in natural resources and in military strategic vantages. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No one can guess which country will fall a victim next to the military aggression launched by the imperialists under a preposterous pretext. This is a stark reality today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Some specific countries do whatever they want while incriminating others when they do something, raising a hue and cry over it as if something terrible has happened. Such woefully abnormal discrimination is the true picture of the international relations today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If interference in the internal affairs of other countries and strong-arm and arbitrary practices are allowed and fostered, the world will be divided into dominating and dominated countries and relations of antagonism and confrontation, domination and subjugation will prevail between them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the imperialists' unreasonable double-standard policy in international affairs which makes the international relations unequal and partial. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 To achieve international unity of the people demanding a new and fair international order is a basic requirement in foiling the imperialists' moves for domination and building a free and peaceful new world.

Greetings to Namibian President 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, sent a message of greetings to Hifikepunye Pohamba, President of Namibia, on March 17 on the occasion of the 17th anniversary of its independence. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In the message Kim sincerely wished the president and people of Namibia continued fresh success in their work for consolidating the socio-economic successes made since independence and steady development and prosperity of the country and expressed the belief that the excellent friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would grow stronger in the future.

Congratulations to Guinean Prime Minister 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- Pak Pong Ju, premier of the DPRK Cabinet, sent a congratulatory message to Lansana Kouyate upon his appointment as Guinean Prime Minister. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Expressing belief that the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries would continue to develop favorably in the future, too, the message sincerely wished him success in his new job.

2007 WWIHC (B Class) Under Way 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- The 2007 World Women's Ice Hockey Championships (B Class) is going on in the way of league match from March 17 in the DPRK amid the great interests of people within and without. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Attending the championships are teams from the DPRK, Italy, Slovakia, Austria, Slovenia and Netherlands which have proved successful in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK team, with good game results, came first in the contest for the qualification for the World Women's Ice Hockey Championships (B Class) held in Hungary in March Juche 89 (2000). &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Italian team is regarded as a likely winner at the current championships and the Slovakian, Austrian and other teams are also strong. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The winner is qualified to participate in the A Class championships. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The players and coaches of the teams are doing the best they can for the title from the beginning of the championships. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is hard to guess which team will become the champion with the game results up to now.

Members of AINDF Pyongyang Mission Visit Revolutionary Museum in Ponghwa-ri
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, March 20 (KCNA) -- Chief Jo Il Min and other members of the Pyongyang mission of the Anti-Imperialist National Democratic Front (AINDF) visited the revolutionary museum in Ponghwa-ri on Tuesday on the occasion of the 90th anniversary of the formation of the Korean National Association by Kim Hyong Jik, an indomitable revolutionary fighter and the outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They laid a bouquet and observed a silent tribute before his statue there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They looked around the relics and materials on display at the museum before going round Myongsin School and other places. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After the visit, Jo Il Min wrote in the visitor's book that the exploits of Kim Hyong Jik, who advanced the noble idea of "Aim High" and devoted his precious life to the sacred cause for the independence of the country and freedom and liberation of the people by leading the KNA, will shine long.

Japanese Authorities Denounced for Suppression and Human Rights Abuses against Chongryon
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tokyo, March 18 (KNS-KCNA) -- A Kyushu district meeting of Koreans in Japan took place in Fukuoka City, Fukuoka Prefecture, on March 10 to denounce the Japanese authorities' unreasonable political suppression and human rights abuses against the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (Chongryon) and Koreans in Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was attended by Chongryon officials, Koreans and students from Fukuoka, Oita, Saga, Kumamoto, Nagasaki, Kagoshima and Miyazaki prefectures and Japanese figures. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The meeting heard a report and indignant speeches. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The reporter and speakers bitterly condemned the fascist atrocities of the Japanese government and police authorities and strongly demanded that the Japanese government stop at once its hostile policy toward the DPRK going against the international political trend and its politically-motivated suppression and human rights abuses against Chongryon and Koreans in Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then followed solidarity speeches of Japanese figures. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They said the Japanese government was hell bent on misinformation against the DPRK through media, but there were 26 societies and friends supporting Korean schools in various parts of Japan. They stated that they would make joint efforts to put an end to the Japanese government's discrimination against and suppression of Koreans through Japan-Korea friendship and solidarity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the end of the meeting its participants started a protest march, chanting slogans, with placards denouncing suppression by the Japanese government. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, representatives of Shiga Korean Primary School including its principal and parents of pupils formed a protest group and staged a protest action against the Osaka Prefectural Police Office on March 8. Koreans and Japanese citizens in Osaka, Kyoto and Hyogo prefectures joined them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The members of the protest group tried to hand to the police authorities a signature paper signed by at least 12,500 Koreans in Japan in protest against the unjustifiable search of Shiga Korean Primary School by the Japanese police authorities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 When police officers refused to accept the signature paper, the enraged members of the protest group staged a fight in front of the Osaka Prefectural Police Office together with Koreans in Japan.

Kim Jong Il inspecciona la comandancia de la Unidad No. 350 del EPC
